      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For a senior dog concerned about weight, you'll want to look for a balanced ratio, but the specifics depend on your lab's individual needs. Generally, a protein level between 25% and 35% is a good starting point for maintaining muscle mass without excessive calories. You'll also want to check the fat content, aiming for something moderate to help with energy without promoting weight gain. Remember, the best food is one that keeps your dog happy and healthy, so observe his condition closely!\n\nIt's always wise to consult your veterinarian; they can give you precise recommendations based on your lab's current body condition score and health profile. They might suggest a specific senior formula designed to manage weight while supporting aging joints. Don't just look at the numbers, but also at the *quality* of the protein sources listed first in the ingredients. A high-quality, digestible protein is more important than just a high percentage.\n\nSpeaking of quality, look for real meat sources—like chicken, beef, or fish—as the primary protein, rather than just \"meat by-products.\" This helps ensure the protein is bioavailable, meaning your lab can actually use it for muscle maintenance. If the food is",
